@NODE Intro "Introduction"

  Whenever you hit a key, move the mouse, insert or remove a disk,
  resize a window, or basically make any kind of input to your computer,
  the operating system creates something that is called an 'input event'.
  That's a structure that is sent to all programs that wish to be informed
  about those things, and it includes all the information about your
  action, ie. the number of the key that you have pressed, the new
  position of your mouse pointer if the mouse has been moved, and so on.

  Now imagine you have to repeat the same input several times, eg. you
  have to type certain commands or click certain gadgets in a specific
  order, and there is, for some reason, no way in which you could
  automate this, by writing a script, for instance.
 
  Here, this program could help you. You could start Recorder, do your
  input once, and this program would save all the input events that have
  been generated by you in a file. Then you could play back all these
  inputs, and to all applications it will look like you are doing
  all inputs again, but actually they are 'fed' into the operating
  system by Recorder.

@ENDNODE  

@NODE Usage "Usage"

  Recorder has no graphical user interface, so you have to start it from
  a command shell. You don't have to use 'Run', as Recorder detaches itself
  automatically from the shell.
  You can start Recorder only once, since multiple copies of it would
  interfere with one another. If you try to start it twice, it will
  tell you it's already running.


  The general parameter pattern of the program is the following:

              Recorder (Rec|Play|App) FILENAME Options 


  The basic operating mode is determined by one of the following:

    @{" REC  " LINK Rec}  Record incoming input events
    @{" PLAY " LINK Play}  Play input events 
    @{" APP  " LINK App}  Append input events to existing file


  The possible options are as follows:

    @{" QUICK  " LINK Quick}  Play back a high speed
    @{" NOWAIT " LINK NoWait}  Start record/play back immediately
    @{" TERSE  " LINK Terse}  Join consecutive mousemove events together 
    @{" QUIET  " LINK Quiet}  Don't give out Display Beeps
    @{" NUM n  " LINK Num}  Play eventfile n times
    @{" QUAL n " LINK Qual}  Set qualifier keys
    @{" PRI n  " LINK Pri}  Set priority of input handler

  
  REC, PLAY, APP, QUICK, NOWAIT and TERSE can be abbreviated by their
  first letter. The order of the options, operating mode and filename does
  not matter.
  With 'Recorder ?' you get a short help.

@ENDNODE
 
@NODE Rec "Operating Mode: Record"

  In this mode, incoming input events are recorded and stored in the file
  with the name FILENAME. If this file doesn't exist, it's created, and
  if it does exist, the old file gets overwritten.

  Unless you specify the @{"NOWAIT" LINK NoWait} option, you have to start recording by
  pressing the @{"start/stop control sequence" LINK SCtrl}.
  You stop recording with the same sequence.

  Events are not written continuously to the file, but stored in two
  internal buffers. See section @{"How does it work ?" LINK HowTo} for more
  information.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Play "Operating Mode: Play back"

  In this mode, input events that were stored in the file FILENAME are
  played back. Each event file has a special header, so if you try to play
  a non-Recorder file, an error will be reported.

  Unless you specify the @{"NOWAIT" LINK NoWait} option, you have to start play back by
  pressing the @{"start/stop control sequence" LINK SCtrl}.
  You can also stop play back with the same sequence.

  The mouse and keyboard are locked while play back is in progress,
  ie. you can't make any inputs yourself (This, of course, does not apply
  to the commands you send to Recorder via key sequences.). That's some
  sort of 'precaution', so that you don't accidentally interfere with play
  back. Because there are mousemove events that only give relative position
  (see section @{"What does Recorder record ?", LINK WhatsRec}), moving the mouse yourself
  would result in the mouse position being not the same as during
  recording, and, for example, a gadget might be missed.


  Note:   The event file format has changed from version 1.2 to 1.3 (See
  -----   @{"History" LINK History} for the reason.). If you try to
          play an old file, Recorder will tell you it's not a valid
          event file.

@ENDNODE

@NODE App "Operating Mode: Append"

  First, the input events that are stored in the file FILENAME are played
  back (see @{"PLAY" LINK Play}), and then more events are recorded and appended to that
  file (see @{"REC" LINK Rec}).
  After play back has finished, a @{"Display Beep", LINK Beep} will be sent to all screens.

  If you specify the option @{"NOWAIT" LINK NoWait}, not only play back will start
  immediately, but also recording after play back. If you don't specify
  this option, you'll have to start recording again after the beep with
  the @{"start/stop control sequence" LINK SCtrl}.

  Note that if you terminate play back early in this mode, you can't add
  more events, ie. Recorder just quits in that case.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Quick "Option: Quick"

  If you choose play or append, the input events are normally played at
  the same speed as they were recorded. However, if you specify this
  option, events are played back as fast as possible, with no delay
  between them.

  But because often a recorded event will result in some other action,
  for example, if you type a name of a program that you want to start,
  the 'Return' event that's generated when you confirm your input with
  the return key will result in this program to start, which will take
  some time. If you make some more input after the program has started,
  like clicking some gadget in that program, and if you play back the
  whole thing later with the QUICK option, you might get surprised.
  Depending on the speed of your computer, Recorder might already feed
  in the clicking of the gadget before the program has actually finished
  starting up. Of course, this is undesirable.
  So be careful with this option !

  This option is ignored in record mode.

@ENDNODE

@NODE NoWait "Option: NoWait"

  If you specify this option, recording or play back will start
  immediately, so you don't have to press the @{"start/stop control sequence" LINK SCtrl}
  first. In append mode, recording after play back will also start
  immediately.

  This option also makes multiple play backs, specified with the option
  @{"NUM" LINK Num}, run continuously.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Terse "Option: Terse"

  Recording some mouse movements, you will notice that the mouse pointer
  usually hoovers around doing nothing most of the time.
  With this option, Recorder will join together these unnecessary events,
  making the pointer movements not only much more straightforward, but also
  reducing the size of the event file considerably (because LOTS of mouse
  move events are usually generated).

  The philosophy behind this option is that moving the mouse pointer
  usually doesn't mean anything if no other key or button is pressed at
  the same time (If some button is pressed, this might well mean something.
  Just draw something in a paint program.). That is, mouse movements are
  often very sloppy, you don't move the mouse in a straight line to its
  destination (Which is good because it shows that you are not a machine.),
  but you 'search', and maybe hesitate. If you play back something that
  has been recorded  without the TERSE option, you will see what I mean.

  Specifying this option makes Recorder effectively omit these 'search'
  movements. The program determines the total distance the mouse has moved
  in a series of mousemove events that didn't involve any other keys,
  and then generates only one absolute mouse event that moves the pointer
  to its final position.
  This means that in this case the type of an event is changed, from
  relative to absolute mouse position. It's not possible to simply add
  up all relative events and generate one of the same type with the sum
  of them all, because a lot of people, including me, use a 'mouse
  accelerator', which means that it is not the same moving the mouse two
  times ten pixels or moving it once twenty pixels.
  However, this changing of event type shouln't make any problems, at
  least I haven't encountered any so far.

  Using this option alone won't speed up play back, because although the
  pointer movements are a lot quicker and more straightforward now, the
  program is still waiting the original time between events that involve
  keys or mouse buttons (Unless you specify the @{"QUICK" LINK Quick} option.).
  So it will happen quite often that after the mouse pointer has moved
  quickly to its destination, nothing will happen for a while. In that case
  you might find the @{"Return" LINK Return} key quite usefull, which will, in play back,
  make Recorder play the next event immediately.

  This option is ignored in play mode.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Quiet "Option: Quiet"

  Specifying this option will suppress all @{"Display Beeps" LINK Beep} to inform the
  user about actions. Therefore, the @{"test control sequence" LINK TCtrl} is also
  disabled.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Num "Option: Num"

  With this option, the events in the specified file are played back
  n times, where n is the number you give with this option.
  A @{"Display Beep" LINK Beep} will be sent out after each cycle.

  If you also specify the @{"NOWAIT" LINK NoWait} option, play back will be
  continuous, otherwise you'll have to start each run with the
  @{"start/stop control sequence" LINK SCtrl}. Pressing this sequence while play
  back is in progress will stop play back altogether.

  Note that the event file is loaded again before every cycle. This is
  necessary because of the internal double buffering (see section
  @{"How does it work ?" LINK HowTo} for details).

  This option is ignored in record or append mode.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Qual "Option: Qual"

  With this option, you can change the qualifier keys for the
  @{"control sequences" LINK Ctrl} that Recorder uses.

  To specify a particular combination, you must add up the appropriate
  numbers from the following list, and give this number with the QUAL
  option:

        Left Shift      1               Right Shift     2
        Left Alt        16              Right Alt       32
        Left Amiga      64              Right Amiga     128
        Control         8

  You can also specify '0', in which case you don't have to press any
  qualifier keys at all, but only the appropriate character. However,
  this is usually not very useful.

  The default is Control-Left Amiga.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Pri "Option Pri"

  You can specify the priority of the input handler here. It must be
  between -128 and +127. The default is 80.

  BEWARE: This is a dangerous option. Especially too low a priority might
          effectively cut off Recorder. The program will start normally,
          but it might be impossible to stop it again since the control
          sequences don't get to the handler anymore.

          USE THIS OPTION WITH CARE OR LEAVE IT ALONE.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Ctrl "Information about control sequences"

  So that Recorder knows when you want it to do something, like when it
  should start recording, for example, it scans the input event stream for
  certain combinations of keys. These usually involve one or more keys of
  the type Shift, Alt, Amiga or Control, called qualifier keys, and one
  normal character. These keys together are called a control sequence.
  The qualifier keys are the same for all commands, but can be chosen via
  the @{"QUAL" LINK Qual} option, whereas the single character that triggers some action
  is fixed. Currently, there are two control sequences:

  @{" Start/Stop Control Sequence " LINK SCtrl}  Qualifier keys + 's'
  @{" Test Control Sequence       " LINK TCtrl}  Qualifier keys + 'd'

  These sequences are filtered out by Recorder, ie. usually other programs
  won't notice anything if you press such a sequence.

  In play back, there is one more special key, which does not need
  qualifiers. That is the @{"Return" LINK Return} key, which is used for playing the
  next event right away.

@ENDNODE

@NODE SCtrl "Start/Stop control sequence"

  This sequence is used to start (unless you specify @{"NOWAIT" LINK NoWait}) and stop
  recording or play back. It is defined as

                        Qualifier keys + 's'.

  If you press this sequence, a @{"Display Beep" LINK Beep} will be sent to all screens.
  You can suppress this by giving the @{"QUIET" LINK Quiet} option.

@ENDNODE

@NODE TCtrl "Test control sequence"

  It might happen that you start Recorder, and then, after a while, you
  aren't sure anymore if you have started recording already or not.
  In that case you can press this control sequence, which is defined as

                        Qualifier keys + 'd'.

  If the program is currently recording or playing back, it will give out
  a @{"Display Beep" LINK Beep}, but it won't do so if it is still waiting for the
  @{"start/stop control sequence" LINK SCtrl}. Of course, if it is recording, this key
  sequence is not recorded.

  This function is disabled by the @{"QUIET" LINK Quiet} option.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Return "The Return key in play back"

  Sometimes you might notice that during play back nothing seems to happen
  for some time. That might be because, during recording, you did wait for
  a few seconds to think about what to do next. You won't notice this,
  unless you actually play back what you've done at the original speed.
  It's often amazing how slow one is !

  However, if you what to skip the current delay, ie. if you want the
  next event to be played right away, you can press the RETURN key, without
  any other qualifiers. This will make Recorder continue with the next
  event, regardless of the original delay after the last event.
  This function is especially usefull if you've recorded something with
  the @{"TERSE" LINK Terse} option, because quite long delays might occur here.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Beep "Information about the use of Display Beeps"
 
  Since Recorder always works in the background, there are not many ways
  to communicate with the user without disturbing other programs.
  Therefore, whenever Recorder wants to inform you about something, it
  sends a 'Display Beep' to all screens, which will make them flash
  visually, and, depending on your system preferences, you will also hear
  a beep.
 
  It does so under the following circumstances:

     1) When you press the @{"start/stop control sequence" LINK SCtrl}.

     2) When you press the @{"test control sequence" LINK TCtrl} and Recorder is
        currently recording or playing.

     3) When play back has finished. In append mode that means that the
        program is now either waiting for the @{"start/stop control sequence" LINK SCtrl},
        or that recording has already started again, depending on the
        @{"NOWAIT" LINK NoWait} option.

     4) When, during recording, the second internal buffer fills up and
        the first one isn't written to the file, yet. Then recording
        terminates, and the events in the internal buffers are saved.
        However, this should usually never happen, even if you are
        writing to a slow floppy disk.
        See section @{"How does it work ?" LINK HowTo} for more information.


  You can suppress display beeps by giving the @{"QUIET" LINK Quiet} option.

@ENDNODE

@NODE WhatsRec "What Does Recorder Record ?"

  Not all possible input events are recorded - it wouldn't make any
  sense to play back a 'disk inserted' event, when there actually hasn't
  been a disk inserted !
  In fact, all that is recorded are keyboard, mousemove and mousebutton
  events, which is enough, since that is all YOU actually do. All the
  other events, like the one indicating the selection of a menu, are
  secondary events. They result from the mouse movement and clicking
  of the right button.

  Actually, sometimes Recorder does record an event which hasn't really
  happened. It is generated by Recorder whenever you start recording.
  You might have noticed that the mouse pointer usually 'jumps' when
  you start play back. This is so because a lot of events generated
  by moving the mouse only give relative positions, ie. the distance
  from the last mouse position. Therefore, it is necessary that the mouse
  pointer is, at the beginning of playback, at the same position as it
  was at the beginning of recording. These relative mouse events are also
  the reason why you can't make any inputs while Recorder is playing,
  because then you might change the current position of the mouse, and
  subsequent relative events would move the pointer to a wrong position.

  If you specify the @{"TERSE" LINK Terse} option, a series of relative mousemove
  events is sometimes changed to one absolute event.

  At the end of each event file, seven more keyboard events are included.
  They 'unpress' the seven possible qualifer keys.
  Because recording is terminated when the @{"start/stop control sequence" LINK SCtrl}
  is detected, the unpressing of the corresponding qualifier keys would not
  be recorded anymore. This might cause trouble with several other programs,
  as they think that, after play back, these keys are still pressed. This
  is prevented by explicitly unpressing them.
  All possible qualifier keys are unpressed, even though usually not all of
  them are involved in the @{"control sequences" LINK Ctrl}. This is only because of the
  ease of implementation (ie. because of my lazyness). It shouldn't really
  cause any trouble, as programs usually look for the pressing of keys, but
  if it does, let me know (see @{"Author" LINK Author} for my address).
  
@ENDNODE

@NODE HowTo "How does it work ?  Input handlers and friends."

  As mentioned in the introduction, every hit of a key and every moving
  of the mouse (and lots of other things) result in an input event
  structure being created by the input device, and these structures are
  send to anyone who has created an input handler to listen to these events.
  As the name implies, these routines handle the events, and do whatever is
  necessary to achive some desired effect.

  This program installs an input handler at high priority (80, if you
  don't change it with the @{"PRI" LINK Pri} option), so that all input
  events pass through this handler first (Unless there is some handler at a
  higher priority, because input events are distributed to the handlers
  in the order of their priority).
  These events are usually passed through unmodified, but also stored first
  in a memory buffer and eventually in a file. The program actually
  uses two buffers, and if one fills up the other one is used while the
  first one is stored on disk, so that continuous recording is possible.
  Should it happen that the second buffer fills up before the first one
  has been written to the file, recording is terminated, and all the
  so far recorded events are saved.
  However, each buffer can hold about 1000 events, and an overflow
  shouldn't occur, even if one writes to a floppy disk and moves the mouse
  rapidly (which creates lots of events).

  In play back mode, the stored events are fed into the input stream
  by the same handler, including some special mouse positioning events
  generated by Recorder. To all handlers listening it looks like you are
  actually doing these inputs.

  And, finally, this handler also deals with the various @{"control sequences" LINK Ctrl},
  and tells the main program about them, and it also blocks the keyboard
  and mouse in play back by simply deleting all events which are coming
  from these sources.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Errors "Startup Errors"

  If Recorder is unable to start up for some reason, it displays an error
  message. Here's a list of what you might see with a few hints on what
  might be wrong:


  "Invalid command line   -   Type 'Recorder ?'"

  Something was wrong with the command line you gave. You might have
  misspelled something, or you've forgotten to give a filename or an
  operating mode.


  "Insufficient free memory"

  Recorder needs about 45 kilobytes of memory. Maybe you're short ?


  "Unable to open file"

  Recorder was unable to open the file you've specified for either reading
  or writing. In the former case, it might simply not exist, in the latter
  you should check if the file or volume you want to write to is not
  write protected.


  "Specified file is not a valid RECORDER file"

  You've tried to play back a file that was not created by Recorder, or one
  that was created with version 1.2 or earlier. These are incompatible with
  the current version.


  "Illegal priority"

  The priority you gave with the @{"PRI" LINK Pri} option wasn't between -128 and +127.


  "Illegal qualifier"

  The number you gave with the @{"QUAL" LINK Qual} option didn't specify a valid
  qualifier.


  "Unable to open intuition library"
  "Unable to install input handler"
  "Unable to open timer device"
  "Unable to open input device"
  "No free signal"

  You shouldn't get any of these errors. If you do, you can't really do
  anything about it, I'm afraid, except telling me.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Problems "Compatibility & Problems"

  The program should work on all Amigas with at least OS2.0.

  It has been reported that recording of the activation of the file gadget
  with the return key in Directory Opus does not work. I don't have an idea
  what to do about this, yet. It might me that Directory Opus isn't using
  the standard input event procedure, in which case Recorder naturally
  fails.

  Currently, the maximum time between two events is 10 years. This should
  not be too much of a limitation, I think.

@ENDNODE

@NODE History "Program history"

  First of all, thanks to the many people who told me about bugs and
  suggested new features, especially to Ashley Powell and Simon Dainty,
  who also did some beta testing for version 1.3 !


  Version 1.4 (May/June 1996)

    - Added @{"QUIET" LINK Quiet} option to suppress display beeps.
    - Added @{"NUM" LINK Num} option to play one event file several times. This also
      takes care of the NOWAIT option.
    - After play back, the qualifier keys got never unpressed, since
      the unpress events weren't recorded anymore. This caused problems
      with several commodities, like AutoCLI. Fixed that by explicitly
      unpressing the qualifers.
    - As you might have realised by now: Documentation is in
      AmigaGuide format. As a user wrote: We are having 1996.
    - Added @{"QUAL" LINK Qual} option to change the control qualifiers.

  Version 1.3 (April 1996)

    - Keyboard and mouse are now locked in playback, so you can't screw
      things up by accidently moving the mouse.
    - Recorder sometimes or always crashed when stopped in playback mode.
      Fixed that.
    - Recorder is now checking if it has already been started.
    - The start/stop sequence is now filtered out to prevent interference
      with other programs that do not ignore this sequence.
    - Changed the whole command line parsing (now uses the function
      ReadArgs() of dos library). This results in a new (better, I'd say ..)
      command line format.
    - Added the opportunity to change the priority of the input handler
      with the @{"PRI" LINK Pri} option.
    - Changed the way the timing is done. This results in a slightly shorter
      event files (One event now uses 22 instead of 26 Bytes.), which also
      makes older event files incompatible. Also, the QUICK option will
      play quicker now.
    - Added @{"NOWAIT" LINK NoWait} option, so that recording/playing might start
      immediately.
    - Added the possibility to check if recording has already been
      initiated by pressing the control qualifiers plus 'd'.
    - Added @{"TERSE" LINK Terse} recording mode.
    - If @{"RETURN" LINK Return} is pressed in play back mode, Recorder will now play the
      next event immediately, ie. it will skip the current delay.
    - Recorder always missed one event when the internal buffers where
      changed. Fixed that.

  Version 1.2 (March 1996)

    - Implemented automatic detaching from the shell.

  Version 1.1 (March 1996)

    - Implemented two internal event buffers.
    - The position of the mouse pointer at the beginning of recording
      is now stored and set in play back.
    - General revision of the program (after all those years ...).

  Version 1.0 (March 1991)

    - First program version; I can't remember if I published this one ?!

@ENDNODE

